metadata.name: Starmap - AI Study I #78
metadata.description:
Starmap brings you to different sectors of the generative art galaxy. A first of its kind generative art experiment using a Text2Code workflow, which involves writing text prompts that get translated into javascript code. This project was created with English words and human imagination, but the programming of the piece is all AI.

The code for this project was written entirely by AI using GPT-3. None of the code was altered or created by a human aside from changing some Math.random() with fxrand().

Text2Code study #1 /// Project CoDexter by @BrainArtLabs

metadata.name: City Pop - AI Study II #229
metadata.description:
City Pop takes you to a lively and geometric city created by digital architects. The use of shapes, colors, and lines causes visionary hallucinations leading the viewer to imaginary places filled with endless possibilities.

This project is a generative art experiment using a Text2Code workflow. The JavaScript code for this project was written entirely by AI using GPT-3. None of the code was altered or created by a human aside from changing Math.random() with fxrand().

Text2Code study #2 /// Project CoDexter by @BrainArtLabs

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #655
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: Charge #184
metadata.description:
Charge is a bridge between engineering and art. It marks beginnings as it is the first long-form algorithm I started developing after joining the NFT and crypto scene. 

The algorithm uncovers the interaction between charged particles in a vacuum, dropping particles in the resulting electromagnetic field showing us a unique view into a subatomic vastness. 

Visually, Charge utilises procedural colour palettes to make each and every piece unique. The layout of the charged particles is another feature that has a large impact on the resulting field and is finely tuned to give a high chance of showcasing a wide range of variations of interacting charges.

metadata.name: Open Concept #143
metadata.description:
We’re just looking for some space. To breathe. To branch out. To connect with and loose yourself.

There are no rarity attributes assigned to this artwork, its value is intended to be determined by viewer aesthetic alone. That aside, there are 9 possible color palettes and background colors.

metadata.name: Unfolded #299
metadata.description:
A plane is repeatedly folded over itself, choosing creases either at random, or according to some pattern (like a grid). These creases form the boundaries of the individual textured tiles.

Once the folds are complete, they are undone in reverse order, recreating the original plane. With each unfolding, the orientation of each crease (as a mountain or a valley), and each tile (facing up or down) is recorded as a sequence of 1s and 0s. Tiles are colored and textured according to similarities in these binary sequences, giving rise to subtle symmetries and repetitions.

Written in vanilla JS & HTML5 Canvas.
